TUnit uses `[Before(...)]` and `[After(...)]` attributes with hook methods, plus class lifecycle interfaces. Here's a sketch for each scope:

## 1. Before every test in a class

```csharp
public class MyTests
{
    [Before(Test)]
    public Task SetUp(TestContext context)
    {
        // Runs before each [Test] in this class
        // e.g. reset in-memory database
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }

    [After(Test)]
    public Task TearDown(TestContext context) => Task.CompletedTask;

    [Test]
    public async Task SomeTest() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## 2. Once before/after all tests in a class (class-scoped fixture)

```csharp
public class MyTests : IAsyncInitializer, IAsyncDisposable
{
    private SqliteConnection _connection = null!;

    // Runs once before the first test in this class
    public async Task InitializeAsync()
    {
        _connection = new SqliteConnection("DataSource=:memory:");
        await _connection.OpenAsync();
    }

    // Runs once after the last test in this class
    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await _connection.DisposeAsync();
    }

    [Test]
    public async Task QueryTest() { /* use _connection */ }
}
```

Alternatively, use `[Before(Class)]` / `[After(Class)]`:

```csharp
public class MyTests
{
    [Before(Class)]
    public static Task BeforeAll(ClassHookContext context) => Task.CompletedTask;

    [After(Class)]
    public static Task AfterAll(ClassHookContext context) => Task.CompletedTask;
}
```

## 3. Once before/after all tests in the assembly

```csharp
public class GlobalSetup
{
    [Before(Assembly)]
    public static async Task StartWireMock(AssemblyHookContext context)
    {
        // Runs once before any test in this assembly
    }

    [After(Assembly)]
    public static async Task StopWireMock(AssemblyHookContext context)
    {
        // Runs once after all tests in this assembly complete
    }
}
```

The class can live anywhere in the assembly — TUnit discovers it automatically. Methods **must be `static`**.

## 4. Once at the very start/end of the entire test session

```csharp
public class SessionLifecycle
{
    [Before(TestSession)]
    public static async Task ApplyMigrations(TestSessionContext context)
    {
        // Runs once at the very start of the test run
    }

    [After(TestSession)]
    public static async Task TearDownDatabase(TestSessionContext context)
    {
        // Runs once at the very end of the test run
    }
}
```

---

### Quick reference

| Scope | Attribute | Method must be | Context parameter |
|-------|-----------|---------------|-------------------|
| Each test | `[Before(Test)]` / `[After(Test)]` | Instance | `TestContext` |
| Class | `[Before(Class)]` / `[After(Class)]` | `static` | `ClassHookContext` |
| Assembly | `[Before(Assembly)]` / `[After(Assembly)]` | `static` | `AssemblyHookContext` |
| Session | `[Before(TestSession)]` / `[After(TestSession)]` | `static` | `TestSessionContext` |

All hook methods return `Task` (or `ValueTask`). The `HookType` enum values (`Test`, `Class`, `Assembly`, `TestSession`) are passed to the attribute constructor. You'll need `using static TUnit.Core.HookType;` (or fully qualify) to use the shorthand shown above.
